So another great way to
engage and retain your users.

00:12:40.700 --> 00:12:43.520
Moving on to the
third fix or tactic,

00:12:43.520 --> 00:12:46.460
and that's probably
my personal favorite,

00:12:46.460 --> 00:12:48.250
making user onboarding great.

00:12:48.250 --> 00:12:51.890
And it also came out
of the Q&amp;A from Peak--

00:12:51.890 --> 00:12:55.160
what is probably the
most important thing

00:12:55.160 --> 00:12:57.350
for engaging users?

00:12:57.350 --> 00:12:59.360
It's user onboarding.

00:12:59.360 --> 00:13:01.070
It's not only my
favorite topic, I also

00:13:01.070 --> 00:13:03.530
have my favorite analogy for it.

00:13:03.530 --> 00:13:08.610
First time user onboarding
is like a first date.

00:13:08.610 --> 00:13:11.960
So basically, you get
all the excitement,

00:13:11.960 --> 00:13:14.180
you get the full,
undivided attention,

00:13:14.180 --> 00:13:16.670
and you can ask all the
questions in the world

00:13:16.670 --> 00:13:20.180
that you want to learn about
the preferences from the other,

00:13:20.180 --> 00:13:22.990
from your user or
from your date.

00:13:22.990 --> 00:13:25.460
You do all this with
only one goal in mind--

00:13:25.460 --> 00:13:26.557
to get another date.

00:13:26.557 --> 00:13:28.640
And then hopefully another
date, and another date,

00:13:28.640 --> 00:13:32.960
and turn this into a
long-lasting relationship.

00:13:32.960 --> 00:13:37.870
But with all that, we
also know-- oh, sorry.

00:13:37.870 --> 00:13:42.980
Too fast-- that it's tricky,
because there's also so

00:13:42.980 --> 00:13:45.110
much room for it to go wrong.

00:13:45.110 --> 00:13:48.170
So what I want to try
to do on the next slide

00:13:48.170 --> 00:13:50.120
is give you some very
simple guidelines

00:13:50.120 --> 00:13:52.100
of things you should
keep in mind when

00:13:52.100 --> 00:13:53.990
you build your onboarding.

00:13:53.990 --> 00:13:57.710
And again, go through your
onboarding along these points,

00:13:57.710 --> 00:14:00.920
and see if you actually meet
the full amount of points

00:14:00.920 --> 00:14:01.940
on all of these.

00:14:01.940 --> 00:14:05.990
So the first one is, it
should be fast and seamless.

00:14:05.990 --> 00:14:07.669
Nothing more
annoying if it really

00:14:07.669 --> 00:14:09.210
takes forever when
I just want to get

00:14:09.210 --> 00:14:12.300
to the actual stuff in the app.

00:14:12.300 --> 00:14:14.960
The second, it
should be contextual

00:14:14.960 --> 00:14:17.750
and it should be part of
the product experience.

00:14:17.750 --> 00:14:22.000
I think that is something that
I still see so many partners

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:27.130
not getting to a full capacity
or doing as good as they can.

00:14:27.130 --> 00:14:29.330
And I'll show you an
example of what I mean.

00:14:29.330 --> 00:14:32.840
And the third is asking
users for minimal user input

00:14:32.840 --> 00:14:35.600
while, on the other hand,
gathering all the information

00:14:35.600 --> 00:14:39.344
you need to actually
create great engagements.

00:14:39.344 --> 00:14:40.760
And I think that's
the tricky bit,

00:14:40.760 --> 00:14:44.870
because it's always a very
fine line you're walking on.

00:14:44.870 --> 00:14:48.530
One fantastic example we see
and we have a feature before,

00:14:48.530 --> 00:14:52.650
I think, is the
fitness app Freeletics.

00:14:52.650 --> 00:14:56.277
So Freeletics, when
you open it up,

00:14:56.277 --> 00:14:57.860
what I really like
about it, it really

00:14:57.860 --> 00:15:00.920
immerses you in
the product world.

00:15:00.920 --> 00:15:02.870
You get to this
screenshot and you

00:15:02.870 --> 00:15:05.330
think the training
has already started,

00:15:05.330 --> 00:15:07.700
even though you don't know
what's coming for you when

00:15:07.700 --> 00:15:08.540
you actually train.

00:15:08.540 --> 00:15:10.240
I just want to say that.

00:15:10.240 --> 00:15:14.480
So they really immerse you
in their product experience

00:15:14.480 --> 00:15:17.164
and they create it for
different user cohorts.

00:15:17.164 --> 00:15:18.830
Basically, you get
to the second screen,

00:15:18.830 --> 00:15:20.990
you select if you are male
or female, and depending

00:15:20.990 --> 00:15:23.380
on that, the tonality
and the screenshots

00:15:23.380 --> 00:15:26.375
and the onboarding
really changes.

00:15:26.375 --> 00:15:28.512
Oh, other way around.

00:15:28.512 --> 00:15:29.720
No, this used to be animated.

00:15:29.720 --> 00:15:33.730
So basically, if you're
a man, after this

00:15:33.730 --> 00:15:38.027
the imagery goes into
that tonality, as well.

00:15:38.027 --> 00:15:39.860
Also what they have
done is, they integrated

00:15:39.860 --> 00:15:41.780
with Google Smart Lock.

00:15:41.780 --> 00:15:45.920
So now, when I use a new device
and I log into Freeletics,

00:15:45.920 --> 00:15:47.600
they automatically sign me in.

00:15:47.600 --> 00:15:49.610
So they basically remove
all the friction for me

00:15:49.610 --> 00:15:52.460
to become a sign-in user and
get that user experience right

00:15:52.460 --> 00:15:53.431
where it left off.

00:15:56.020 --> 00:16:01.700
A very quick run through of
what Google Smart Lock can do.

00:16:01.700 --> 00:16:05.150
From left to right, this is
the experience a new user has.

00:16:05.150 --> 00:16:06.990
The new user registers.

00:16:06.990 --> 00:16:08.360
They click to register.

00:16:08.360 --> 00:16:09.777
They select an email address.

00:16:09.777 --> 00:16:11.360
It could be any
address that they have

00:16:11.360 --> 00:16:15.242
saved with Android or Chrome.

00:16:15.242 --> 00:16:17.450
Then Smart Lock fills in
the gaps-- obviously outside

00:16:17.450 --> 00:16:18.410
of the password.

00:16:18.410 --> 00:16:20.120
The user gets to
choose it themselves.

00:16:20.120 --> 00:16:21.020
They're logged in.

00:16:21.020 --> 00:16:22.970
And then on the
last screen, they

00:16:22.970 --> 00:16:27.290
can decide if they want to save
the passwords to Smart Lock.

00:16:27.290 --> 00:16:30.930
And actually,
across all the apps,

00:16:30.930 --> 00:16:35.900
we see, I think, 65% of users
actually saving their passwords

00:16:35.900 --> 00:16:37.280
and then they're in that system.

00:16:37.280 --> 00:16:40.110
That makes it really
easy for them.

00:16:40.110 --> 00:16:43.484
We also have two
really cool case

00:16:43.484 --> 00:16:45.650
studies on that, which I'm
just going to talk about.

00:16:45.650 --> 00:16:46.733
They're not on this slide.

00:16:46.733 --> 00:16:49.250
But [INAUDIBLE] which
is outdoor activity app,

00:16:49.250 --> 00:16:52.310
they did an A/B test where
they tested Google Smart

00:16:52.310 --> 00:16:54.800
Lock a sign-in versus
another sign-in,

00:16:54.800 --> 00:16:58.460
and they had a 19% increase
in sign-up conversion

00:16:58.460 --> 00:16:59.510
with Smart Lock.

00:16:59.510 --> 00:17:01.010
And the second one
is Zalando, which

00:17:01.010 --> 00:17:03.290
is the shopping
app, that see 20%

00:17:03.290 --> 00:17:08.990
of the current sign-in events
are automatic by Smart Lock.

00:17:08.990 --> 00:17:12.140
So if this is one
of your aims, and I

00:17:12.140 --> 00:17:14.540
think most partners
do really push

00:17:14.540 --> 00:17:16.480
for getting users
logged in, then this

00:17:16.480 --> 00:17:18.727
is definitely something
to consider for you.

00:17:21.710 --> 00:17:25.295
As I said, onboarding is not
only important-- it's not only

00:17:25.295 --> 00:17:27.170
my favorite topic, it's
also super important.

00:17:27.170 --> 00:17:30.040
So with all super important
things in your app,

00:17:30.040 --> 00:17:32.750
you should test, test,
and test again, right?

00:17:32.750 --> 00:17:34.100
And iterate and test again.

00:17:34.100 --> 00:17:37.310
And another tool that I
want to show you for that

00:17:37.310 --> 00:17:43.030
is Firebase Remote Config that
lets you run A/B experiments.

00:17:43.030 --> 00:17:45.710
It lets you custom control
key values within your app,

00:17:45.710 --> 00:17:48.590
and the change-- everything
you change basically

00:17:48.590 --> 00:17:49.820
goes live instantly.

00:17:49.820 --> 00:17:52.670
So if you are familiar with
the [INAUDIBLE] Firebase Suite,

00:17:52.670 --> 00:17:54.620
that's another
handy tool to look

00:17:54.620 --> 00:17:57.160
into to to actually optimize
the onboarding workflow.

00:17:57.160 --> 00:17:59.647
Also any other part in
your app, quite frankly.

00:18:02.540 --> 00:18:08.620
So quick recap before I
move into the next one.

00:18:08.620 --> 00:18:10.130
We're at number four now.

00:18:10.130 --> 00:18:13.440
The first one was having
a clear value proposition.

00:18:13.440 --> 00:18:16.610
Second one, leveraging
the full Android platform.

00:18:16.610 --> 00:18:19.280
Third one, make great
user onboarding.

00:18:19.280 --> 00:18:21.980
And number four is
actually about successfully

00:18:21.980 --> 00:18:23.060
releasing new feature.

00:18:23.060 --> 00:18:25.640
And I call it the kind of
younger sister or younger

00:18:25.640 --> 00:18:27.620
brother of user onboarding
because there are so

00:18:27.620 --> 00:18:30.920
many similarities in
how to think about it.

00:18:30.920 --> 00:18:35.180
First of all, you remember from
the slide on reasons to churn

00:18:35.180 --> 00:18:37.100
is, you've got to stay fresh.

00:18:37.100 --> 00:18:37.650
Right?

00:18:37.650 --> 00:18:38.608
And you guys know this.

00:18:38.608 --> 00:18:40.460
You're leading developers
in your industry.

00:18:40.460 --> 00:18:43.070
You know there is somebody
coming for you, essentially,

00:18:43.070 --> 00:18:44.910
and you've got to move
ahead of the curve.

00:18:44.910 --> 00:18:46.760
You've got to come
up with new features.

00:18:46.760 --> 00:18:48.840
If you are about
content, you constantly

00:18:48.840 --> 00:18:52.100
need to push new
content in order

00:18:52.100 --> 00:18:53.930
to stay relevant to users.

00:18:53.930 --> 00:18:57.270
So that's a very general
advice on that, which I think

00:18:57.270 --> 00:18:58.520
most of you are familiar with.

00:19:01.370 --> 00:19:05.900
When you do introduce
new features or content,

00:19:05.900 --> 00:19:09.470
what I think is a very
simple and systematic release

00:19:09.470 --> 00:19:14.960
methodology to follow is
to first of all test it

00:19:14.960 --> 00:19:17.570
with beta users-- that
was mentioned before--

00:19:17.570 --> 00:19:20.640
to make sure that it actually
works on retention engagement

00:19:20.640 --> 00:19:22.370
metrics.

00:19:22.370 --> 00:19:26.310
Secondly, again, ensure
technical stability.

00:19:26.310 --> 00:19:28.580
Thirdly, really show
users what's new,

00:19:28.580 --> 00:19:31.010
and that's actually what
the screenshot here is for.

00:19:31.010 --> 00:19:32.750
Imagine you had never
seen this product

00:19:32.750 --> 00:19:35.000
and you were introduced to
this and you could actually

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:37.730
navigate from here if
you're driving your car.

00:19:37.730 --> 00:19:40.490
There are some very easy
ways, with material design,

00:19:40.490 --> 00:19:43.550
to make this visually very
simple and light weight,

00:19:43.550 --> 00:19:46.910
but yet very clear to users when
they onboard to a new feature.

00:19:46.910 --> 00:19:49.160
And then, as a fourth
point, obviously analyze

00:19:49.160 --> 00:19:51.639
the performance.

00:19:51.639 --> 00:19:53.180
Again, we have a
couple of tools that

00:19:53.180 --> 00:19:57.330
are super useful for that
For point number one and two,

00:19:57.330 --> 00:20:01.220
beta groups and
prelaunch reports,

00:20:01.220 --> 00:20:03.140
both were featured in
large this morning.

00:20:03.140 --> 00:20:04.681
I'm not going to go
into them, I just

00:20:04.681 --> 00:20:07.370
want to give it a big
fat plus one or plus

00:20:07.370 --> 00:20:10.040
two, depending on how
you want to see it.

00:20:10.040 --> 00:20:12.080
On prelaunch reports,
actually keep in mind

00:20:12.080 --> 00:20:13.520
that you need to opt in.

00:20:13.520 --> 00:20:15.270
So it's not going to
happen automatically.

00:20:15.270 --> 00:20:17.750
So you need to go
in the console,

00:20:17.750 --> 00:20:20.600
opt in for it to be activated,
and then every single thing you

00:20:20.600 --> 00:20:25.160
upload to alpha/beta
actually runs these checks.

00:20:25.160 --> 00:20:29.240
And then use cohort analysis
in Firebase Analytics

00:20:29.240 --> 00:20:32.270
or in Google Analytics to
really check the performance

00:20:32.270 --> 00:20:33.490
of new features.

00:20:33.490 --> 00:20:35.210
It's one thing that
you built something

00:20:35.210 --> 00:20:37.070
new and fancy and
cool, but you really

00:20:37.070 --> 00:20:38.840
want to make sure
that you actually

00:20:38.840 --> 00:20:42.470
optimize against that goal
for retention or engagement

00:20:42.470 --> 00:20:43.370
that you have.

00:20:43.370 --> 00:20:47.050
And as always, numbers are
best way to make a decision.

00:20:51.380 --> 00:20:55.940
Another point you may recall
from the list we showed

00:20:55.940 --> 00:20:59.990
of reasons why users churn is
that your app-- or an app--

00:20:59.990 --> 00:21:04.130
may be too interchangeable with
what t competitor is offering.

00:21:04.130 --> 00:21:06.770
One really cool
way to counter this

00:21:06.770 --> 00:21:09.240
is to personalizing
the experience,

00:21:09.240 --> 00:21:12.530
so to make the
user feel at home.

00:21:12.530 --> 00:21:14.840
I think there are two
main way of doing this.

00:21:14.840 --> 00:21:17.250
Number one is
where you basically

00:21:17.250 --> 00:21:20.810
give the user all
kinds of manual ways

00:21:20.810 --> 00:21:23.900
to design the experience.

00:21:23.900 --> 00:21:26.840
You may like let them toggle
stuff in the home screen,

00:21:26.840 --> 00:21:29.400
switch stuff on and off, and
so on, and I think all of that

00:21:29.400 --> 00:21:30.680
is great.

00:21:30.680 --> 00:21:33.080
Just what I think happens
quite a lot, or what we hear

00:21:33.080 --> 00:21:35.760
happens quite a lot, that
really remains something

00:21:35.760 --> 00:21:38.090
that mostly power
users do, and it's

00:21:38.090 --> 00:21:40.670
really hard to get average
or the broad range of users

00:21:40.670 --> 00:21:43.740
actually to do that.

00:21:43.740 --> 00:21:48.530
So another way to do this is by
actually doing personalization,

00:21:48.530 --> 00:21:51.890
by using business intelligence
to individualize the product

00:21:51.890 --> 00:21:52.880
experience.

00:21:52.880 --> 00:21:56.370
And I will show you
what that means.

00:21:56.370 --> 00:21:58.500
A great example for this
that was shared with me,

00:21:58.500 --> 00:22:02.860
actually, was from hotels.com.

00:22:02.860 --> 00:22:05.270
They basically
anticipate user-- or they

00:22:05.270 --> 00:22:08.330
use user behavior to
anticipate users' needs,

00:22:08.330 --> 00:22:10.340
and provide the
relevant experience

00:22:10.340 --> 00:22:11.840
in the right moments.

00:22:11.840 --> 00:22:13.230
So what does that mean?

00:22:13.230 --> 00:22:15.170
They try to map
various scenarios

00:22:15.170 --> 00:22:17.300
for users coming into the app.

00:22:17.300 --> 00:22:18.950
One is onboarding.

00:22:18.950 --> 00:22:20.570
When it's about
onboarding, they try

00:22:20.570 --> 00:22:22.910
to make it as convenient
as possible for the user

00:22:22.910 --> 00:22:25.880
to actually go to sign-in.

00:22:25.880 --> 00:22:29.346
When a user actually
comes back to the app--

00:22:29.346 --> 00:22:31.470
so it's a returning user
that has searched before--

00:22:31.470 --> 00:22:34.190
and they may show them something
that's relevant to their search

00:22:34.190 --> 00:22:35.900
or where they were left off.

00:22:35.900 --> 00:22:38.550
And then another scenario could
be that somebody has actually

00:22:38.550 --> 00:22:42.320
booked a hotel with
hotels.com, and on the day

00:22:42.320 --> 00:22:43.940
of check-in or
check-out, they will

00:22:43.940 --> 00:22:46.010
provide relevant
information, maybe

00:22:46.010 --> 00:22:48.770
around where people
travel, or stuff around

00:22:48.770 --> 00:22:49.910
the hotel and information.

00:22:49.910 --> 00:22:52.850
So they have different
scenarios where the user really

00:22:52.850 --> 00:22:54.920
feels like this
is a personalized

00:22:54.920 --> 00:22:55.910
experience to them.

00:22:58.550 --> 00:23:00.500
How they do that
is, first of all,

00:23:00.500 --> 00:23:05.300
by being aware of all of that
and actually catering for it,

00:23:05.300 --> 00:23:08.450
but also by creating a
flexible content structure

00:23:08.450 --> 00:23:12.320
that actually allows them to
move around content and modules

00:23:12.320 --> 00:23:15.920
to react to this broad
range of scenarios.

00:23:15.920 --> 00:23:19.350
And then the third one, is that
they actually exhaustively map

00:23:19.350 --> 00:23:22.170
the context, instead of content
or action the user was left in.

00:23:22.170 --> 00:23:23.878
So that when you leave
and you come back,

00:23:23.878 --> 00:23:28.386
you really feel like you're
continuing where you left off.

00:23:28.386 --> 00:23:29.760
So I think that's
a great example

00:23:29.760 --> 00:23:32.930
of using data and a
sophisticated technical

00:23:32.930 --> 00:23:35.790
approach to actually
provide personal user

00:23:35.790 --> 00:23:39.410
experience for a broad range.

00:23:39.410 --> 00:23:42.560
Some of you may probably think
now, oh, you said easy fixes.

00:23:42.560 --> 00:23:43.700
This seems very complex.

00:23:43.700 --> 00:23:44.330
Yes.

00:23:44.330 --> 00:23:46.790
This is probably one of
the things that are not

00:23:46.790 --> 00:23:51.170
that straightforward and easy
to set up, but once you have it,

00:23:51.170 --> 00:23:55.260
it's actually a very neat way
to do that personalization.

00:23:55.260 --> 00:23:58.510
So I think it's really worth
the effort of looking into that.

00:24:02.910 --> 00:24:05.399
The second last I want
to talk about is having

00:24:05.399 --> 00:24:06.940
a great communication
strategy and it

00:24:06.940 --> 00:24:11.210
ties very much into the
personalization bit.

00:24:11.210 --> 00:24:14.460
So push notifications is
what I'm going to focus on,

00:24:14.460 --> 00:24:18.760
and they have become somewhat
the standard on the platform

00:24:18.760 --> 00:24:21.060
as an engagement tool,
and rightfully so.

00:24:21.060 --> 00:24:23.620
They work great if you
do a great job on them.

00:24:23.620 --> 00:24:25.870
However, there's
also a fine line

00:24:25.870 --> 00:24:29.590
between using them to drive
engagement, on the one hand,

00:24:29.590 --> 00:24:32.990
or to actually make users churn
because you're overdoing it

00:24:32.990 --> 00:24:36.060
or they're not relevant
or whatever it may be.

00:24:36.060 --> 00:24:38.710
So again, some very
simple rules in order

00:24:38.710 --> 00:24:41.530
to make the strategy successful.

00:24:41.530 --> 00:24:45.110
First, the push notification
needs to be relevant.

00:24:45.110 --> 00:24:48.580
So the context, the
language, the tonality

00:24:48.580 --> 00:24:50.690
needs to be relevant
to the user.

00:24:50.690 --> 00:24:53.210
And be creative, be
true to your brand.

00:24:53.210 --> 00:24:54.280
Be creative.

00:24:54.280 --> 00:24:57.440
Speak to the customer
in a unique way.

00:24:57.440 --> 00:25:01.210
I think that's something that
I still see a lot of partners

00:25:01.210 --> 00:25:03.824
not fully optimizing.

00:25:03.824 --> 00:25:05.240
Second, it needs
to be actionable.

00:25:05.240 --> 00:25:06.607
Is it an FYI?

00:25:06.607 --> 00:25:07.940
Is it actually a call to action?

00:25:07.940 --> 00:25:09.400
Do you want me to do something?

00:25:09.400 --> 00:25:11.885
If so, then make sure
that is deeplinked

00:25:11.885 --> 00:25:13.510
and that when I
actually click through,

00:25:13.510 --> 00:25:15.250
I get to whatever
you talked about.

00:25:15.250 --> 00:25:18.060
Because if that's not happened,
then the user experience

00:25:18.060 --> 00:25:20.290
is really burned, and
you're like, OK, where am I?

00:25:20.290 --> 00:25:21.107
Why am I here?

00:25:21.107 --> 00:25:22.940
And you're probably not
going to do it again

00:25:22.940 --> 00:25:27.550
or you're less likely to push
on opening the app again.

00:25:27.550 --> 00:25:32.020
Then third one is-- I want to
talk about timeliness first.

00:25:32.020 --> 00:25:34.840
Timeliness, the right
message at the right time.

00:25:34.840 --> 00:25:36.580
Again, it seems
very obvious, but I

00:25:36.580 --> 00:25:38.829
think the London Olympics--
oh, not the London, sorry.

00:25:38.829 --> 00:25:41.390
The Rio Olympics were a
great example of that.

00:25:41.390 --> 00:25:44.860
A lot of the stuff happened
overnight for users in EMEA.

00:25:44.860 --> 00:25:50.240
So the question becomes, is
it that Usain Bolt won the 100

00:25:50.240 --> 00:25:50.740
meters?

00:25:50.740 --> 00:25:52.540
Or somebody broke
a world record?

00:25:52.540 --> 00:25:54.640
Is that really more
relevant at 3:00

00:25:54.640 --> 00:25:56.710
AM in the morning
on a Tuesday night?

00:25:56.710 --> 00:25:59.000
Or should you be waiting
to push that message

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:02.020
at 7:00 AM in the morning when
you know your users get up

00:26:02.020 --> 00:26:04.132
and actually check their news?

00:26:04.132 --> 00:26:05.590
So there are things
to keep in mind

00:26:05.590 --> 00:26:08.330
and not only go, oh, this is a
great thing, I'll just push it

00:26:08.330 --> 00:26:10.645
out, because it may lose
its effect on users.

00:26:13.540 --> 00:26:17.770
And then the fourth
point is personalization.

00:26:17.770 --> 00:26:20.740
You should segment users,
you should have your cohorts,

00:26:20.740 --> 00:26:24.640
and then also proactively
let users opt out of stuff

00:26:24.640 --> 00:26:26.890
and opt into other stuff.

00:26:26.890 --> 00:26:29.350
Especially the opt out part
seems counter-intuitive,

00:26:29.350 --> 00:26:32.650
but let me give you one
great example where-- which

00:26:32.650 --> 00:26:33.960
you see on the left, actually.

00:26:33.960 --> 00:26:35.660
This is a screenshot
of Aftenposten.

00:26:35.660 --> 00:26:39.460
It's one of the biggest
newspapers in the Nordics.

00:26:39.460 --> 00:26:42.070
And they basically--
a while ago, they

00:26:42.070 --> 00:26:45.410
redid their whole onboarding,
and as part of that,

00:26:45.410 --> 00:26:48.670
a new notification
management screen and they

00:26:48.670 --> 00:26:50.380
saw some fantastic results.

00:26:50.380 --> 00:26:52.080
So basically, now
when you onboard,

00:26:52.080 --> 00:26:54.652
users get to select to-- I
think this is pre-selected

00:26:54.652 --> 00:26:56.860
and then they get to opt
out, but they're proactively

00:26:56.860 --> 00:26:59.980
asked to do so.

00:26:59.980 --> 00:27:02.060
So what they saw
is, first of all,

00:27:02.060 --> 00:27:05.470
that I think over 50%
of the users actually

00:27:05.470 --> 00:27:07.309
keep two of the three.

00:27:07.309 --> 00:27:09.850
So they take one off consciously
but they take the other ones

00:27:09.850 --> 00:27:11.530
because they think
they're relevant.

00:27:11.530 --> 00:27:14.050
And then, overall, they saw
a decrease of uninstalls

00:27:14.050 --> 00:27:18.220
by, I think, 9% over
60 days, which I think

00:27:18.220 --> 00:27:21.100
is a strong argument
for the point I tried

00:27:21.100 --> 00:27:24.100
to make earlier where too many
push notifications, or not

00:27:24.100 --> 00:27:27.400
having a strategy, can be
really be something that leads

00:27:27.400 --> 00:27:30.250
to churn, while it should be
really something that helps you

00:27:30.250 --> 00:27:32.230
engage and retain users.

00:27:32.230 --> 00:27:34.196
And then also, another
interesting side effect,

00:27:34.196 --> 00:27:36.070
is that they really
learned about their users

00:27:36.070 --> 00:27:39.370
and the preferences
of those users.

00:27:39.370 --> 00:27:41.830
And to my surprise,
apparently there

00:27:41.830 --> 00:27:44.320
were less users
interested in sports

00:27:44.320 --> 00:27:45.878
than in the other topics.

00:27:45.878 --> 00:27:48.086
For me, usually, that's
exactly the other way around.

00:27:51.910 --> 00:27:53.290
Again, just to
highlight one tool

00:27:53.290 --> 00:27:55.120
that you can use
for that very well,

00:27:55.120 --> 00:28:00.520
is Firebase Cloud Messaging.

00:28:00.520 --> 00:28:03.400
It lets you target individual
devices, cohorts, and so on.

00:28:03.400 --> 00:28:06.070
Super reliable and
it's cross-platform.

00:28:06.070 --> 00:28:07.450
It doesn't only
work for Android,

00:28:07.450 --> 00:28:09.910
so you can use it across
the platforms-- [INAUDIBLE]

00:28:09.910 --> 00:28:13.250
and iOS, as well.

00:28:13.250 --> 00:28:19.630
Last but not least,
rewarding use engagement.

00:28:19.630 --> 00:28:21.250
Let's talk a bit about that.

00:28:21.250 --> 00:28:26.710
I think, very generally, this
should be something everybody

00:28:26.710 --> 00:28:30.610
should be thinking about from
the perspective of making

00:28:30.610 --> 00:28:34.540
it really desirable for
your users to become

00:28:34.540 --> 00:28:37.000
an engaged user with you.

00:28:37.000 --> 00:28:39.280
And when they are
engaged user, really

00:28:39.280 --> 00:28:41.380
reward them and show
you that you value that.

00:28:44.740 --> 00:28:46.810
Obviously it's a
topic, and this is

00:28:46.810 --> 00:28:49.780
something I realized more than
ever when I started researching

00:28:49.780 --> 00:28:51.790
it for this talk,
that you can go

00:28:51.790 --> 00:28:55.270
really deep in when it comes to
gamification and the mechanics

00:28:55.270 --> 00:28:56.920
around it and so on, right?

00:28:56.920 --> 00:28:58.420
And there are many
great strategies,

00:28:58.420 --> 00:29:00.970
and probably with a
lot of the gaming guys

00:29:00.970 --> 00:29:03.790
here, they could go on
about this for length

00:29:03.790 --> 00:29:06.280
and without any end.

00:29:06.280 --> 00:29:09.580
However, it can already start
with very simple rewards

00:29:09.580 --> 00:29:10.870
mechanism.

00:29:10.870 --> 00:29:12.160
It's a broad range.

00:29:12.160 --> 00:29:15.070
It's a large spectrum
of stuff you can do.

00:29:15.070 --> 00:29:19.210
And what works for your app
really depends on your app,

00:29:19.210 --> 00:29:21.870
on your industry, what
business model you have,

00:29:21.870 --> 00:29:24.890
a free [INAUDIBLE], and so on.

00:29:24.890 --> 00:29:27.830
However, if you're not
doing anything at all,

00:29:27.830 --> 00:29:30.490
and I think you
should, then you can

00:29:30.490 --> 00:29:32.440
start with keeping
it very simple,

00:29:32.440 --> 00:29:36.640
thinking of something that adds
value to your users, and makes

00:29:36.640 --> 00:29:38.890
sense and fits with
your overlap ecosystem.

00:29:38.890 --> 00:29:43.510
So a couple of good examples
are inviting power users

00:29:43.510 --> 00:29:47.062
to early access to test
beta features and so on.

00:29:47.062 --> 00:29:48.520
Give them a special
preview, right?

00:29:48.520 --> 00:29:51.952
It's a very simple one, but you
wouldn't believe how many users

00:29:51.952 --> 00:29:52.660
really love that.

00:29:52.660 --> 00:29:54.201
And I do it for a
lot of the products

00:29:54.201 --> 00:29:56.620
that I love, too, where I
proactively tell the developer,

00:29:56.620 --> 00:29:59.350
please include me
in product testing

00:29:59.350 --> 00:30:02.410
just because I love
the product so much.

00:30:02.410 --> 00:30:04.930
The second one are badges.

00:30:04.930 --> 00:30:05.860
How do I know that?

00:30:05.860 --> 00:30:07.570
Because you guys all love it.

00:30:07.570 --> 00:30:10.690
Whenever it's about a badge on
Google Play, people go crazy.

00:30:10.690 --> 00:30:15.310
Top Developer Badge,
Editor's Choice, and so on.

00:30:15.310 --> 00:30:18.232
And usually the ones that
go most crazy are the devs.

00:30:18.232 --> 00:30:19.690
Maybe sometimes
the business people

00:30:19.690 --> 00:30:21.310
we talk to, they're
like what's the impact?

00:30:21.310 --> 00:30:21.720
What's that?

00:30:21.720 --> 00:30:23.260
And they talk about
all these numbers,

00:30:23.260 --> 00:30:24.160
and then we talk about that.

00:30:24.160 --> 00:30:26.560
But then, when they get it,
they tell me, oh, my Android

00:30:26.560 --> 00:30:27.550
developers freaked out.

00:30:27.550 --> 00:30:30.430
We're like best of that,
we're part of here.

00:30:30.430 --> 00:30:32.699
So really giving
these simple badges.

00:30:32.699 --> 00:30:34.240
Usually it doesn't
cost you anything,

00:30:34.240 --> 00:30:35.210
it just needs--
you need to come up

00:30:35.210 --> 00:30:36.590
with a structure
on how to do it,

00:30:36.590 --> 00:30:39.430
and you can really show
users how valued they are.

00:30:39.430 --> 00:30:41.350
And then you can do
stuff like offering app

00:30:41.350 --> 00:30:44.110
exclusive discounts.

00:30:44.110 --> 00:30:46.060
Generally, the more
you can endeavor

00:30:46.060 --> 00:30:48.400
individualize that, the better.

00:30:48.400 --> 00:30:50.510
But again, starting off
with a very broad range

00:30:50.510 --> 00:30:52.660
and basically just
showing users that you

00:30:52.660 --> 00:30:54.590
value that they are
there and go from there,

00:30:54.590 --> 00:30:56.120
is a really good start.

00:30:56.120 --> 00:30:57.840
The bottom line
is, these engaged

00:30:57.840 --> 00:31:01.000
users are your best customer
and they should be valued.

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:03.266
Because who does not
like to be valued?

00:31:06.280 --> 00:31:11.915
So here are the seven
fixes again in an overview.

00:31:11.915 --> 00:31:13.540
I think you had enough
from me for now.

00:31:13.540 --> 00:31:16.537
This was quite a lot
of input, I think.

00:31:16.537 --> 00:31:18.370
So it's time for some
first-hand experience,

00:31:18.370 --> 00:31:20.536
and I would like to welcome
Markus Falk from Lifesum

00:31:20.536 --> 00:31:21.522
up on stage.

00:31:21.522 --> 00:31:26.260
