00:32:02.830 --> 00:32:04.750
tells you how good
is your product.

00:32:04.750 --> 00:32:08.200
I mean, if your users are coming
back, it's a good product.

00:32:08.200 --> 00:32:12.100
So that's the one metric that
should be above everyone else,

00:32:12.100 --> 00:32:14.950
I think.

00:32:14.950 --> 00:32:18.040
So we're just going to give you
a bit of an insight around how

00:32:18.040 --> 00:32:21.100
we think around retention
at Lifesum and engagement.

00:32:21.100 --> 00:32:22.930
So starting off
with a little bit

00:32:22.930 --> 00:32:26.380
about us, but also what
retention engagement

00:32:26.380 --> 00:32:28.600
means to health in specific.

00:32:28.600 --> 00:32:32.980
Then a little bit of what we
track and why we track it.

00:32:32.980 --> 00:32:35.710
And then I have two
examples, one where we tested

00:32:35.710 --> 00:32:38.920
and failed miserably and
the other one where we

00:32:38.920 --> 00:32:40.960
tested and actually succeeded.

00:32:40.960 --> 00:32:42.820
It's nice that you can
set off this agenda,

00:32:42.820 --> 00:32:46.060
because it looks like it's
a 50/50 split there, which

00:32:46.060 --> 00:32:48.780
might not always be the case.

00:32:48.780 --> 00:32:52.490
And then I'm rounding
up with a few takeaways.

00:32:52.490 --> 00:32:54.490
So start with a bit about us.

00:32:54.490 --> 00:32:57.250
I think there are a few
things within health

00:32:57.250 --> 00:32:58.510
that needs to be fixed.

00:32:58.510 --> 00:33:03.670
So today, health care is
actually a lot about sick care.

00:33:03.670 --> 00:33:07.050
You wait until you get sick
and then you get treated.

00:33:07.050 --> 00:33:08.740
But instead, it
should be that you

00:33:08.740 --> 00:33:10.420
do a lot of stuff
with your lifestyle

00:33:10.420 --> 00:33:12.550
before you actually get sick.

00:33:12.550 --> 00:33:16.300
I mean, the way you eat, how you
train, exercise, how you sleep,

00:33:16.300 --> 00:33:18.552
stress levels, et cetera,
will affect your life.

00:33:18.552 --> 00:33:20.260
So that's basically
what we are here for.

00:33:20.260 --> 00:33:24.700
We are here to sort
of help you with that

00:33:24.700 --> 00:33:27.490
But then when we talk about
engagement and retention

00:33:27.490 --> 00:33:29.440
I think it's kind
of interesting when

00:33:29.440 --> 00:33:31.840
it comes to health
because no one has really

00:33:31.840 --> 00:33:34.970
sold it in a good way.

00:33:34.970 --> 00:33:38.170
And I don't think that's
all about just health apps.

00:33:38.170 --> 00:33:40.710
I think it's for the
health sector, in general.

00:33:40.710 --> 00:33:41.920
Let's take gyms for example.

00:33:41.920 --> 00:33:44.710
I think in the US
you have about 70%

00:33:44.710 --> 00:33:46.540
of people that own a
gym subscription isn't

00:33:46.540 --> 00:33:47.910
going to the gym.

00:33:47.910 --> 00:33:51.370
And you have-- when it comes
to medication or medical

00:33:51.370 --> 00:33:54.950
and pharma-- about 50% of
people who are on medication

00:33:54.950 --> 00:33:56.710
isn't taking them properly.

00:33:56.710 --> 00:33:58.690
So the challenge
is, how do you get

00:33:58.690 --> 00:34:01.780
people to think it's
interesting and fun to take

00:34:01.780 --> 00:34:03.130
care of themselves?

00:34:03.130 --> 00:34:03.967
Which is hard.

00:34:03.967 --> 00:34:05.800
But of course, within
this sort of industry,

00:34:05.800 --> 00:34:08.030
you can be either good or
you can be bad at this.

00:34:08.030 --> 00:34:10.530
And I think that Lifesum
is-- we're not the worst.

00:34:10.530 --> 00:34:12.730
We're definitely not
the best, either.

00:34:12.730 --> 00:34:16.780
But for us, it's definitely--
the number one company

00:34:16.780 --> 00:34:18.130
goal is to work on retention.

00:34:18.130 --> 00:34:20.360
It's the stuff that we
talk about every day.

00:34:20.360 --> 00:34:21.790
It's definitely the key for us.

00:34:21.790 --> 00:34:24.190
So we haven't figured it
out, but we are trying

00:34:24.190 --> 00:34:27.920
to do a lot of stuff around it.

00:34:27.920 --> 00:34:30.969
So a little bit about what
we track and why we track it.

00:34:30.969 --> 00:34:32.607
So we have a few
standard metrics

00:34:32.607 --> 00:34:33.940
that we follow on a daily basis.

00:34:33.940 --> 00:34:36.070
So we look at seven
day retention.

00:34:36.070 --> 00:34:37.600
We look at week five retention.

00:34:37.600 --> 00:34:39.670
And we look at
week 53 retentions.

00:34:39.670 --> 00:34:42.462
Of course we do deep dives,
et cetera, within those,

00:34:42.462 --> 00:34:44.170
but these are the ones
that are standard.

00:34:44.170 --> 00:34:47.980
So what we noticed was that when
the users come into the Lifesum

00:34:47.980 --> 00:34:50.073
app a lot of them
has actually decided

00:34:50.073 --> 00:34:52.239
that they want to change
something with their lines.

00:34:52.239 --> 00:34:53.488
They want to become healthier.

00:34:53.488 --> 00:34:56.469
So they're super engaged
in that very first moment

00:34:56.469 --> 00:34:58.000
when they come into the app.

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:00.910
But then what we've seen is
that they rapidly drop off

00:35:00.910 --> 00:35:02.610
during the first seven days.

00:35:02.610 --> 00:35:04.810
So for us, the number
one metric to follow

00:35:04.810 --> 00:35:07.720
has been the 7-day metric.

00:35:07.720 --> 00:35:09.310
But then, most
recently, we've started

00:35:09.310 --> 00:35:12.070
to think a little bit
different around retention.

00:35:12.070 --> 00:35:15.834
That you shouldn't really treat
it the same way for all users

00:35:15.834 --> 00:35:17.500
because it's kind of
different depending

00:35:17.500 --> 00:35:18.730
on what you want to achieve.

00:35:18.730 --> 00:35:20.980
So we looked at
the data and we see

00:35:20.980 --> 00:35:24.050
that we have basically four
different types of users--

00:35:24.050 --> 00:35:27.300
the monster, the focused, the
dieter, and the long term.

00:35:27.300 --> 00:35:28.000
I named them.

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:32.230
So let's say the
dieter for example.

00:35:32.230 --> 00:35:35.650
In the US, the average American
goes on a diet about four times

00:35:35.650 --> 00:35:38.610
a year, which is quite a lot.

00:35:38.610 --> 00:35:40.170
It's crazy, I know.

00:35:40.170 --> 00:35:43.920
And that diet will last from
anywhere between a few days

00:35:43.920 --> 00:35:45.790
to a few weeks.

00:35:45.790 --> 00:35:47.620
So for us, then, it's important.

00:35:47.620 --> 00:35:51.010
So instead of trying to force
the dieters behavior to become

00:35:51.010 --> 00:35:55.000
the monster, which is tracking
every day for several months,

00:35:55.000 --> 00:35:57.730
we should just recognize,
OK, this person is on a diet.

00:35:57.730 --> 00:35:59.740
We need to make the
app as good as possible

00:35:59.740 --> 00:36:02.740
for them to come back
for the next diet.

00:36:02.740 --> 00:36:04.960
So that sort of
thinking, like OK,

00:36:04.960 --> 00:36:07.420
if we can put these people
in different buckets,

00:36:07.420 --> 00:36:10.780
we should treat
them differently.

00:36:10.780 --> 00:36:13.730
So two examples.

00:36:13.730 --> 00:36:17.380
Let's start with a sad one.

00:36:17.380 --> 00:36:20.050
So we had this knowledge
about that users are very

00:36:20.050 --> 00:36:21.770
motivated in their first visit.

00:36:21.770 --> 00:36:23.710
So we thought that
if we can get them

00:36:23.710 --> 00:36:28.250
to invest a lot of time and
energy in the app at first,

00:36:28.250 --> 00:36:30.020
they will be coming back.

00:36:30.020 --> 00:36:33.460
So we basically created
this massive health test

00:36:33.460 --> 00:36:34.570
of 41 questions.

00:36:34.570 --> 00:36:37.270
We brought in consultants,
nutritionists, et cetera.

00:36:37.270 --> 00:36:38.870
We built it into
the onboarding flow.

00:36:38.870 --> 00:36:40.440
We put it on the profile page.

00:36:40.440 --> 00:36:43.420
We prompted it several times.

00:36:43.420 --> 00:36:44.530
It was a massive project.

00:36:44.530 --> 00:36:48.797
It took us months to develop.

00:36:48.797 --> 00:36:51.380
And then when we release it, of
course, we were super excited.

00:36:51.380 --> 00:36:54.640
This is going to have a massive
impact on seven-day retention.

00:36:54.640 --> 00:36:57.710
And now everyone's just waiting
for the data and when it came,

00:36:57.710 --> 00:37:00.250
it was the sound of
no hands clapping.

00:37:00.250 --> 00:37:02.290
Nothing happened.

00:37:02.290 --> 00:37:05.870
So of course, it
was a big failure.

00:37:05.870 --> 00:37:07.840
But then of course, with
failures, you usually

00:37:07.840 --> 00:37:09.770
get some stuff out of it.

00:37:09.770 --> 00:37:12.340
For us it was, I
think, first we managed

00:37:12.340 --> 00:37:15.170
to confirm that we have the
high initial motivation.

00:37:15.170 --> 00:37:19.270
So out of the people starting
the test, we had about 90%

00:37:19.270 --> 00:37:21.770
completing all 41 questions.

00:37:21.770 --> 00:37:25.570
So within a few weeks, we had a
million of these test results,

00:37:25.570 --> 00:37:27.831
and that data is
kind of valuable.

00:37:27.831 --> 00:37:29.830
I mean, first of all,
this info you can see, OK,

00:37:29.830 --> 00:37:32.300
how many percent is a
vegetarian in London compared

00:37:32.300 --> 00:37:33.920
to Stockholm, for example.

00:37:33.920 --> 00:37:36.770
But also referring to the
buckets that I talked about,

00:37:36.770 --> 00:37:40.210
we can actually profile
users now based on this data.

00:37:40.210 --> 00:37:42.440
So it's something that
we're not doing yet

00:37:42.440 --> 00:37:44.080
the way we should be
doing it, but it's

00:37:44.080 --> 00:37:45.645
a really interesting source.

00:37:45.645 --> 00:37:49.190
But of course, from a retention
perspective, it wasn't good.

00:37:49.190 --> 00:37:52.010
And I think what we learned from
that is also what the guys have

00:37:52.010 --> 00:37:53.770
been talking about before.

00:37:53.770 --> 00:37:56.830
You need to find
ways of testing stuff

00:37:56.830 --> 00:37:58.763
before you put a lot
of effort into it.

00:38:01.350 --> 00:38:05.150
So we often did stuff
that was working out.

00:38:05.150 --> 00:38:09.340
So going back a few
months, we didn't really

00:38:09.340 --> 00:38:12.905
have any sort of social
interaction in the app.

00:38:12.905 --> 00:38:15.280
And I think the reason for
that was that we didn't really

00:38:15.280 --> 00:38:18.440
know what people wanted to
share, because when it comes

00:38:18.440 --> 00:38:21.670
to your personal health,
especially around weight loss,

00:38:21.670 --> 00:38:24.232
it's not that you want to
like-- you don't want to share

00:38:24.232 --> 00:38:25.190
everything on Facebook.

00:38:25.190 --> 00:38:27.020
Let's put it that way.

00:38:27.020 --> 00:38:28.730
So what we did here
is that we created

00:38:28.730 --> 00:38:33.820
this very small, intimate
social feature, very simple,

00:38:33.820 --> 00:38:35.570
and we ran a test in Sweden.

00:38:35.570 --> 00:38:38.350
So it's basically that you
could invite up to five friends

00:38:38.350 --> 00:38:40.510
to become your sort of team.

00:38:40.510 --> 00:38:43.600
And within that team you could
basically push each other

00:38:43.600 --> 00:38:46.190
and motivate each other, but
you could also remind people

00:38:46.190 --> 00:38:49.310
if they were dropping off.

00:38:49.310 --> 00:38:52.940
So when we got that out, we
saw that people on social

00:38:52.940 --> 00:38:56.690
actually had a 2x increase
in seven-day retention, which

00:38:56.690 --> 00:38:58.540
was, of course, fantastic.

00:38:58.540 --> 00:39:02.729
But if you think about it, it's
like if you have five people,

00:39:02.729 --> 00:39:05.020
and three of them drop off,
and they have two more that

00:39:05.020 --> 00:39:07.070
can keep reminding
them, that's always

00:39:07.070 --> 00:39:10.190
going to be better than if
you have like five silos where

00:39:10.190 --> 00:39:11.590
no one can talk.

00:39:11.590 --> 00:39:15.510
So from that perspective,
it was really good.

00:39:15.510 --> 00:39:18.650
What we had some issues with
there was the adoption rate.

00:39:18.650 --> 00:39:22.810
We didn't really got that
many users to be on social.

00:39:22.810 --> 00:39:25.790
So we popped a survey
for them who declined

00:39:25.790 --> 00:39:28.250
and the reason
was still privacy.

00:39:28.250 --> 00:39:29.650
I don't want to share my data.

00:39:29.650 --> 00:39:33.730
So this is still a big challenge
for us to try to figure out,

00:39:33.730 --> 00:39:38.270
but also massive potential.

00:39:38.270 --> 00:39:42.230
So yeah, wrapping
up a little bit.

00:39:42.230 --> 00:39:46.000
I mean, looking at your
own users' retention

00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:46.790
is interesting.

00:39:46.790 --> 00:39:49.730
So not just treating
retention the same way

00:39:49.730 --> 00:39:52.160
across different apps or
even across your own users

00:39:52.160 --> 00:39:55.120
or try to find what
are your patterns.

00:39:55.120 --> 00:39:57.207
For us, it might be very
high initial motivation

00:39:57.207 --> 00:39:59.040
or that we have a lot
of dieters in the app,

00:39:59.040 --> 00:40:01.540
but it might be
different for you.

00:40:01.540 --> 00:40:03.880
And then social is key.

00:40:03.880 --> 00:40:09.000
If you can get your own users
to help you with retention,

00:40:09.000 --> 00:40:14.251
it's always going to be good,
referring to the health test

00:40:14.251 --> 00:40:14.750
that we did.

00:40:14.750 --> 00:40:16.750
And I think that
everyone is saying this

00:40:16.750 --> 00:40:18.610
but it needs to be said
over and over again,

00:40:18.610 --> 00:40:22.500
is that you need to find
easy, quick ways of testing

00:40:22.500 --> 00:40:25.020
your ideas before
you spend hundreds

00:40:25.020 --> 00:40:28.080
and thousands on building them.

00:40:28.080 --> 00:40:28.690
Cool.

